The paper proposes a machine learning model for environmental monitoring, which involves understanding and modeling environmental phenomena. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a Gaussian Process (GP) model, which is a common technique used in machine learning for regression and classification tasks. This further supports the likelihood of the paper belonging to the cs.LG sub-category. 

The paper also deals with spatio-temporal data, which suggests that it could belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) or Statistics (cs.ST) sub-categories. The paper proposes a non-stationary model, which involves learning variable length scales, suggesting that it could belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves empirical validation using real-world datasets, which suggests that it could belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Therefore, the 5 likely arXiv CS sub-categories for this paper, ordered from most to least likely, are cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.CV, cs.ST, and cs.NE.
